And now we want to finish
the day by taking a moment

00:01:03.526 --> 00:01:05.646 A:middle
to celebrate the work that some

00:01:05.646 --> 00:01:07.536 A:middle
of you have done that's
been extraordinary.

00:01:07.916 --> 00:01:10.426 A:middle
Many of you do -- all of
you do extraordinary work,

00:01:10.466 --> 00:01:13.376 A:middle
but there are some that
stand out from the rest,

00:01:13.376 --> 00:01:15.296 A:middle
and we want to take
a few moments

00:01:15.336 --> 00:01:17.996 A:middle
to just celebrate some
excellence in software design.

00:01:18.656 --> 00:01:22.956 A:middle
Now, to begin this
evening and this ceremony,

00:01:22.956 --> 00:01:26.806 A:middle
I want to just kick off with a
video, which is a retrospective

00:01:26.806 --> 00:01:29.426 A:middle
of the winners from
the last 14 years.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:23.636 --> 00:03:26.536 A:middle
You know, time flies;
doesn't it?

00:03:26.956 --> 00:03:30.826 A:middle
How many of you are familiar
with so many of those apps?

00:03:30.916 --> 00:03:32.456 A:middle
You played with those games.

00:03:33.066 --> 00:03:34.896 A:middle
You played with those
productivity tools,

00:03:34.896 --> 00:03:36.636 A:middle
some of those design tools.

00:03:37.006 --> 00:03:38.416 A:middle
And I had to demo
every one of them

00:03:38.416 --> 00:03:40.446 A:middle
on this stage over the years.

00:03:40.766 --> 00:03:44.336 A:middle
And this is just some
of those that came --

00:03:44.336 --> 00:03:47.146 A:middle
that you saw a moment ago coming
through for the last 14 years.

00:03:47.536 --> 00:03:51.186 A:middle
Those 14 years represent
14 years of Design Awards

00:03:51.186 --> 00:03:55.346 A:middle
since OS X was announced,
Mac OS X entered the stage,

00:03:55.546 --> 00:03:58.276 A:middle
and we had developers creating
apps right from day one.

00:03:58.776 --> 00:04:00.796 A:middle
And then, of course, the
App Store came and iOS

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.776 --> 00:04:00.796 A:middle
And then, of course, the
App Store came and iOS

00:04:00.796 --> 00:04:02.526 A:middle
and everything that
we've known since then.

00:04:02.996 --> 00:04:05.656 A:middle
So many of you might be familiar
with the most recent ones

00:04:05.656 --> 00:04:09.076 A:middle
that were shown, and if you
just take a look at this list --

00:04:09.076 --> 00:04:12.276 A:middle
and this isn't to pick off
the best of the 14 years --

00:04:12.276 --> 00:04:14.296 A:middle
but these are some notable
ones that I just wanted

00:04:14.296 --> 00:04:15.216 A:middle
to highlight for a minute.

00:04:16.646 --> 00:04:20.396 A:middle
You know, Starry Night Backyard,
I remember showing that off.

00:04:20.396 --> 00:04:24.476 A:middle
That was incredible in the
first days of Mac OS X.

00:04:24.476 --> 00:04:28.576 A:middle
Macnification, this
great app for science.

00:04:28.576 --> 00:04:32.336 A:middle
Delicious Library 2, this
whole genre of apps that came

00:04:32.336 --> 00:04:35.606 A:middle
out in the early days of Mac OS
X that redefined the experience

00:04:35.606 --> 00:04:39.236 A:middle
for so many of us and actually
forced -- well, not forced --

00:04:39.236 --> 00:04:40.996 A:middle
but got people excited

00:04:40.996 --> 00:04:43.796 A:middle
to purchase a Mac just
to use those apps.

00:04:43.846 --> 00:04:45.666 A:middle
MLB.com At Bat.

00:04:45.666 --> 00:04:47.216 A:middle
Flight Control.

00:04:47.216 --> 00:04:49.326 A:middle
Who didn't play Flight
Control in the first days

00:04:49.376 --> 00:04:51.536 A:middle
of the App Store, right?

00:04:51.536 --> 00:04:54.946 A:middle
Paper for scientific research,
and then Monument Valley,

00:04:55.256 --> 00:04:58.346 A:middle
Infinity Blade, incredible apps.

00:04:58.956 --> 00:05:05.686 A:middle
What's interesting is that
these apps have set the standard

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:58.956 --> 00:05:05.686 A:middle
What's interesting is that
these apps have set the standard

00:05:05.686 --> 00:05:07.616 A:middle
for so many things; right?

00:05:07.956 --> 00:05:09.976 A:middle
They've set the standard
for the user experience

00:05:09.976 --> 00:05:12.176 A:middle
that we expect on
these platforms.

00:05:12.596 --> 00:05:17.046 A:middle
These folks were pioneers in
many ways, not just these apps,

00:05:17.046 --> 00:05:20.056 A:middle
but the apps that showed up
across the last 14 years.

00:05:20.576 --> 00:05:23.766 A:middle
And I think the -- what's really
cool way to think about it is

00:05:23.766 --> 00:05:27.686 A:middle
that in so many ways, each of
the winners each year stood

00:05:27.946 --> 00:05:31.196 A:middle
on the shoulders of the
winners from the previous year.

00:05:31.936 --> 00:05:34.646 A:middle
Because so many of these
apps defined a new standard,

00:05:34.916 --> 00:05:37.616 A:middle
a benchmark in performance
or in usability,

00:05:37.986 --> 00:05:40.926 A:middle
and they inspired the rest of
you, inspired so many people

00:05:41.306 --> 00:05:43.096 A:middle
to go off and create
the next great thing.

00:05:44.346 --> 00:05:49.406 A:middle
Now, these apps every
year we've judged the apps

00:05:49.406 --> 00:05:51.486 A:middle
with the same set of
criteria, basically.

00:05:51.916 --> 00:05:53.846 A:middle
We've looked at delightful apps.

00:05:53.906 --> 00:05:55.796 A:middle
These are apps that
invite people to play

00:05:55.796 --> 00:05:58.066 A:middle
or get real things done; right?

00:05:58.066 --> 00:05:59.986 A:middle
They are satisfying;
they are rewarding.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:00.956 --> 00:06:02.876 A:middle
We've always looked
for innovative apps,

00:06:02.876 --> 00:06:07.686 A:middle
winners that have this spark
of brilliance that it's hard

00:06:07.686 --> 00:06:10.606 A:middle
to define, but you know
it when you see it.

00:06:11.156 --> 00:06:13.606 A:middle
There's state-of-the-art
apps that are modern.

00:06:13.726 --> 00:06:15.776 A:middle
They are platform
differentiating.

00:06:16.126 --> 00:06:20.426 A:middle
They're high performance; they
have high-end capabilities,

00:06:20.426 --> 00:06:21.786 A:middle
and they are superprecise.

00:06:23.326 --> 00:06:25.056 A:middle
We look for apps
that are engaging.

00:06:25.576 --> 00:06:28.006 A:middle
Engagement means that
people keep coming back

00:06:28.136 --> 00:06:29.126 A:middle
to use these apps.

00:06:29.536 --> 00:06:30.886 A:middle
Some of the games
that were shown,

00:06:30.886 --> 00:06:32.586 A:middle
some of the productivity
tools are things

00:06:32.586 --> 00:06:33.776 A:middle
that we can't live without.

00:06:34.386 --> 00:06:36.076 A:middle
We can't live without
playing these games,

00:06:36.076 --> 00:06:37.906 A:middle
and we keep coming back
to them again and again.

00:06:38.916 --> 00:06:41.126 A:middle
We look for apps
that are enabling.

00:06:41.176 --> 00:06:44.426 A:middle
And great Apple Design
Award-winning apps

00:06:44.806 --> 00:06:47.186 A:middle
that are enabling
allow you to do things

00:06:47.186 --> 00:06:49.926 A:middle
that you could never
do before in new ways.

00:06:50.136 --> 00:06:53.096 A:middle
And lastly, we look
for designed apps.

00:06:53.566 --> 00:06:57.206 A:middle
These are apps that are deeply
considered, that are familiar,

00:06:57.596 --> 00:07:00.096 A:middle
they're appealing,
they're attractive,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:57.596 --> 00:07:00.096 A:middle
they're appealing,
they're attractive,

00:07:00.406 --> 00:07:02.756 A:middle
and they're super intuitive
to use for the people

00:07:02.756 --> 00:07:03.946 A:middle
that they were created for.

00:07:05.016 --> 00:07:07.806 A:middle
So, a quick summary of
how we pick the apps.

00:07:07.936 --> 00:07:10.386 A:middle
We've always picked them
in basically the same way.

00:07:10.386 --> 00:07:12.916 A:middle
We've always used essentially
this set of criteria,

00:07:13.556 --> 00:07:16.786 A:middle
and this is the criteria
that we used for this year

00:07:17.146 --> 00:07:19.356 A:middle
to pick tonight's winners.

00:07:19.676 --> 00:07:23.016 A:middle
I'd like to invite my
colleague, Shaan Pruden,

00:07:23.086 --> 00:07:26.456 A:middle
on stage to award
tonight's winners.

00:07:27.516 --> 00:07:35.016 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:07:35.516 --> 00:07:35.976 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN: Hello.

00:07:36.746 --> 00:07:39.656 A:middle
This year we will be honoring
ten apps from categories

00:07:39.656 --> 00:07:42.936 A:middle
across the App Store, but first
we wanted to take a moment

00:07:43.186 --> 00:07:45.976 A:middle
and honor two students among
our scholarship winners.

00:07:46.556 --> 00:07:49.816 A:middle
&gt;&gt; JOHN GELEYNSE: Now,
the students we are

00:07:49.816 --> 00:07:53.246 A:middle
about to award are scholarship
winners for this year,

00:07:53.916 --> 00:07:56.476 A:middle
but in the process of looking
at the scholarship apps,

00:07:57.006 --> 00:07:58.996 A:middle
we discovered some apps
that they, themselves,

00:07:58.996 --> 00:08:00.716 A:middle
had also written
for the App Store,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.996 --> 00:08:00.716 A:middle
had also written
for the App Store,

00:08:01.206 --> 00:08:03.316 A:middle
and we were pretty impressed
with some of these apps

00:08:03.356 --> 00:08:05.476 A:middle
that were on the App Store
by these scholarship winners.

00:08:05.476 --> 00:08:08.166 A:middle
So the two awards
tonight are going to go

00:08:08.236 --> 00:08:10.046 A:middle
to developer scholarship winners

00:08:10.086 --> 00:08:11.186 A:middle
who have an app on
the App Store.

00:08:11.686 --> 00:08:14.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN: And our first
student winner is Elementary

00:08:14.666 --> 00:08:16.086 A:middle
Minute by Klemens Strasser.

00:08:16.316 --> 00:08:24.066 A:middle
&gt;&gt; The idea for the
app came to Klemens

00:08:24.306 --> 00:08:30.326 A:middle
in April 2014 while
sitting in his room thinking

00:08:30.326 --> 00:08:32.446 A:middle
about the possibility of
having a quiz on his wrist.

00:08:32.446 --> 00:08:34.356 A:middle
Since there wasn't
an Apple Watch yet,

00:08:34.696 --> 00:08:36.956 A:middle
Klemens developed
it for the iPhone.

00:08:43.515 --> 00:08:49.616 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:08:50.116 --> 00:08:50.896 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN:
Congratulations.

00:08:51.676 --> 00:08:54.096 A:middle
Here you go.

00:08:54.316 --> 00:08:56.726 A:middle
Elementary Minute is a
fast-paced trivia game

00:08:56.776 --> 00:08:59.006 A:middle
where you are presenting
with statements on topics

00:08:59.006 --> 00:09:01.526 A:middle
that include math,
geography, and famous people.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.006 --> 00:09:01.526 A:middle
that include math,
geography, and famous people.

00:09:02.006 --> 00:09:03.536 A:middle
Quickly swipe up
or down to decide

00:09:03.536 --> 00:09:05.166 A:middle
if the statements
are true or false.

00:09:05.506 --> 00:09:06.876 A:middle
This app was created by Klemens,

00:09:06.876 --> 00:09:08.086 A:middle
who is a computer
science student

00:09:08.086 --> 00:09:10.156 A:middle
at Technical University
in Graz, Austria.

00:09:11.516 --> 00:09:16.656 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:09:17.156 --> 00:09:17.696 A:middle
&gt;&gt; JOHN GELEYNSE:
Austria, right.

00:09:18.316 --> 00:09:19.656 A:middle
Big cheer down in front here.

00:09:20.006 --> 00:09:22.696 A:middle
We Picked Elementary Minute as
a student Design Award winner

00:09:22.696 --> 00:09:26.796 A:middle
because we loved the design, it
was super simple, and it was one

00:09:26.796 --> 00:09:30.416 A:middle
of the first games that
came out for Apple Watch.

00:09:30.986 --> 00:09:34.326 A:middle
It's built, obviously, on UIKit
and those sorts of technologies.

00:09:34.326 --> 00:09:35.746 A:middle
It's integrated with
Game Center,

00:09:35.746 --> 00:09:38.286 A:middle
and it has a clever
two-game mode.

00:09:38.286 --> 00:09:41.906 A:middle
You can do a quick five-second
quiz, trivia quiz on your wrist,

00:09:41.906 --> 00:09:42.946 A:middle
which is perfect for the Watch,

00:09:43.446 --> 00:09:46.016 A:middle
and you can do a one-minute
quiz both on Apple Watch

00:09:46.176 --> 00:09:48.356 A:middle
and on iPhone, and
we just thought

00:09:48.356 --> 00:09:51.846 A:middle
that the way this was done
was really well executed,

00:09:51.846 --> 00:09:52.926 A:middle
so congratulations.

00:09:53.616 --> 00:09:54.736 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN: And
that's Elementary Minute.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:01.416 --> 00:10:03.436 A:middle
Our other student
Award this evening goes

00:10:03.516 --> 00:10:06.446 A:middle
to jump-O by ByteBrushers.

00:10:07.516 --> 00:10:11.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:10:12.046 --> 00:10:15.696 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Founded in 2013, ByteBrushers
is a two-person game development

00:10:15.776 --> 00:10:16.926 A:middle
team located in Brazil.

00:10:17.196 --> 00:10:21.076 A:middle
In 2012, Victor took a
game development course,

00:10:21.436 --> 00:10:23.276 A:middle
and a year later,
he convinced Gabriel

00:10:23.456 --> 00:10:25.286 A:middle
to attend the same course.

00:10:25.866 --> 00:10:28.416 A:middle
One day while discussing what it
was like when they were bullied

00:10:28.416 --> 00:10:30.346 A:middle
as kids, they decided
to create a game

00:10:30.346 --> 00:10:31.846 A:middle
that reflected their experience.

00:10:40.166 --> 00:10:40.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN:
Congratulations.

00:10:45.396 --> 00:10:46.836 A:middle
Jump-O is a minimalist game

00:10:46.836 --> 00:10:48.346 A:middle
where you play Roundy
the circle,

00:10:48.346 --> 00:10:51.106 A:middle
overcoming the dangers presented
by the squareish world.

00:10:51.686 --> 00:10:54.296 A:middle
It was created by two
university students from Brazil

00:10:54.296 --> 00:10:56.206 A:middle
and features beautiful
hand-drawn puzzles.

00:10:58.126 --> 00:10:59.066 A:middle
&gt;&gt; JOHN GELEYNSE: You
know what's really fun

00:10:59.066 --> 00:11:01.586 A:middle
for us actually at Apple
is these folks took some

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:59.066 --> 00:11:01.586 A:middle
for us actually at Apple
is these folks took some

00:11:01.586 --> 00:11:03.976 A:middle
of the iOS training
courses that are in Brazil

00:11:03.976 --> 00:11:07.196 A:middle
and gained some experience
there to build this game.

00:11:07.416 --> 00:11:10.326 A:middle
We picked jump-O as a
student Design Award winner

00:11:10.326 --> 00:11:14.066 A:middle
because of its unique minimalist
design, as Shaan mentioned.

00:11:14.396 --> 00:11:16.936 A:middle
It's built on Game
Center, it uses Sprite Kit

00:11:16.936 --> 00:11:19.586 A:middle
for scene management
and game physics.

00:11:19.976 --> 00:11:21.886 A:middle
The input of the
game is super simple.

00:11:21.886 --> 00:11:23.756 A:middle
It's tap and device motion.

00:11:24.086 --> 00:11:28.206 A:middle
And it's got great
responsiveness, 68 worlds,

00:11:28.206 --> 00:11:31.486 A:middle
48 levels, just a
really fun game

00:11:31.696 --> 00:11:34.326 A:middle
that we thought was just
really, really well done,

00:11:34.326 --> 00:11:36.536 A:middle
and one of those games
that seems easy to learn

00:11:36.856 --> 00:11:39.706 A:middle
but it's hard to
master in that genre.

00:11:39.706 --> 00:11:41.936 A:middle
So congratulations,
great work, guys.

00:11:42.516 --> 00:11:49.606 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:11:50.106 --> 00:11:51.746 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN: And these
are our two student winners.

00:11:52.326 --> 00:11:54.596 A:middle
Now let's move on to the
Design Award winners.

00:11:55.796 --> 00:12:05.156 A:middle
Our first winner is an
imagination-stirring puzzle.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:55.796 --> 00:12:05.156 A:middle
Our first winner is an
imagination-stirring puzzle.

00:12:05.616 --> 00:12:08.976 A:middle
It is Shadowmatic by
Triada Studio Games.

00:12:15.026 --> 00:12:18.206 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Triada Studio was
established in Armenia in 1993

00:12:18.576 --> 00:12:20.366 A:middle
as a computer graphics
and animation studio,

00:12:20.366 --> 00:12:23.546 A:middle
and they successfully work on
TV commercials, visual effects

00:12:23.606 --> 00:12:26.116 A:middle
for movies, and various
other animation projects.

00:12:26.196 --> 00:12:28.856 A:middle
In 2007, they thought about
branching into video games,

00:12:28.906 --> 00:12:30.506 A:middle
began building a game engine.

00:12:30.566 --> 00:12:32.526 A:middle
The four-person game
team started work

00:12:32.526 --> 00:12:36.966 A:middle
on Shadowmatic in March 2012.

00:12:38.876 --> 00:12:40.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; SHAAN PRUDEN:
Shadowmatic is a unique twist

00:12:40.666 --> 00:12:41.806 A:middle
on shadow puppets.

00:12:42.386 --> 00:12:43.366 A:middle
I don't want to stand
in their way.

00:12:44.876 --> 00:12:47.236 A:middle
Rotate abstract objects
in a spotlight

00:12:47.576 --> 00:12:50.496 A:middle
to find recognizable silhouettes
in the projected shadow

00:12:50.496 --> 00:12:52.646 A:middle
that are relevant to the
surrounding environment.

00:12:56.056 --> 00:12:56.616 A:middle
&gt;&gt; JOHN GELEYNSE: All right.

00:12:56.616 --> 00:12:58.556 A:middle
So we picked Shadowmatic
as a winner

00:12:58.556 --> 00:13:03.516 A:middle
since it's ornately crafted
-- bit of feedback --

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:58.556 --> 00:13:03.516 A:middle
since it's ornately crafted
-- bit of feedback --

00:13:03.876 --> 00:13:06.666 A:middle
super imaginative, and
really well executed.

00:13:06.796 --> 00:13:09.356 A:middle
And I'd like to show
this to you now.

00:13:10.186 --> 00:13:12.446 A:middle
So let's get into the
level -- let's turn it off.

00:13:12.576 --> 00:13:15.216 A:middle
Let's get into the main menu.

00:13:15.286 --> 00:13:18.866 A:middle
So what you see here is just
there's device motion that's

00:13:18.866 --> 00:13:22.456 A:middle
affecting the view
into this main menu.

00:13:22.666 --> 00:13:24.936 A:middle
I can interact with objects,
which is no big deal,

00:13:24.936 --> 00:13:26.256 A:middle
but I am just showing
you the attention

00:13:26.256 --> 00:13:28.616 A:middle
